<div id="review_2032066731" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2032066731" />
    <a title="J. Sebastian" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5744897-j-sebastian"><img alt="J. Sebastian" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1529334439p2/5744897.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2032066731?book_show_action=true">Jun 17, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="J. Sebastian" class="user" itemprop="url" name="J. Sebastian" href="/user/show/5744897-j-sebastian">J. Sebastian</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780151005956" href="/book/show/953394.The_Tale_of_the_Unknown_Island">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5744897-j-sebastian?shelf=childhood">childhood</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2032066731" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8331612847251992829"><i>“They said there are no more unknown islands and that, even if there were, they weren’t prepared to leave the comfort of their homes and the good life on board passenger ships just to get involved in some oceangoing adventure, looking for the impossible, as if we were still living in the days when the sea was dark, And what did you say to them, That the sea is always dark, And you didn’t tell them about the unknown island, How could I tell them about an unknown island, if I don’t even know where</i></span>
  <span id="freeText8331612847251992829" style="display:none"><i>“They said there are no more unknown islands and that, even if there were, they weren’t prepared to leave the comfort of their homes and the good life on board passenger ships just to get involved in some oceangoing adventure, looking for the impossible, as if we were still living in the days when the sea was dark, And what did you say to them, That the sea is always dark, And you didn’t tell them about the unknown island, How could I tell them about an unknown island, if I don’t even know where it is, But you’re sure it exists, As sure as I am that the sea is dark, . . .”</i><br /><br />Interesting use of punctuation to present the dialogue. There are no periods or question marks; the change of speaker is indicated by a new capital letter. In this way Saramago weaves a dreamlike narrative, short and interesting, at times delightful, upon which the reader too floats like a ship at sea. <i>“I want to find the unknown island, I want to find out who I am when I’m there on that island, Don’t you know, If you don’t step outside yourself, you’ll never discover who you are. . .”</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="8331612847251992829" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


