<div id="review_651778435" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/651778435" />
    <a title="Lloyd Fassett" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4478202-lloyd-fassett"><img alt="Lloyd Fassett" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1550687857p2/4478202.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/651778435?book_show_action=true">Jun 26, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lloyd Fassett" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lloyd Fassett" href="/user/show/4478202-lloyd-fassett">Lloyd Fassett</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4478202-lloyd-fassett?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer651778435" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7159451550995085051">This is my favorite fable. It&apos;s about a couple of people that go in pursuit of the &quot;unknown island&quot;. They are not lost. They do it on purpose only to have the ship they are on turn into the island they were looking for itself. <br/><br/>It&apos;s for entrepreneurs or better put, it&apos;s for anyone who searches. It&apos;s the act of searching, of being driven from the inside, that is its own reward. The finding, achieving, graduating, selling, being the King (close to him), financial statements, are all trailing indica</span>
  <span id="freeText7159451550995085051" style="display:none">This is my favorite fable. It's about a couple of people that go in pursuit of the "unknown island". They are not lost. They do it on purpose only to have the ship they are on turn into the island they were looking for itself. <br /><br />It's for entrepreneurs or better put, it's for anyone who searches. It's the act of searching, of being driven from the inside, that is its own reward. The finding, achieving, graduating, selling, being the King (close to him), financial statements, are all trailing indicators highly correlated with how things have been done. Leading indicators are feedback on how things will be done, but are 'leading' because they haven't been discovered yet. Once discovered, they are trailing. The endpoint isn't defined. Once it is, the cycle can continue again. Some people just like to go for the Unknown Islands.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7159451550995085051" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


